The ČSSD in Prague knows neither Voldemort nor the pastries
The new CSSD councillors in the capital will appear to have to overcome the obvious language barriers for the components of the Prague Board and the municipal council to understand their renewed SDG companions.
The period Aktuálně.cz "examined" members of the new Council of the ČSSD to check their knowledge of the marked slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The codified dictionary that used the political flower and cream of Prague during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councillors hardly understand these well-known concepts.
At least, they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"The truth is, I don't know."
"I am rather a novice in Prague politics," he said during the "college" terminology exam of Culture Councillor Lukáš Kaucký.
And as far as the political veteran is concerned, Karel Březina reacted the same way.
Perhaps you know the concept of golf hole.
"It's possibly the only expression of all you asked me to use from time to time."
"If not, I don't usually employ slang."
From the glossary, the definitions of which the newspaper Aktuálně.cz published last June before the SDG voting congress, the draft selected six examples, in particular those that are especially related to the municipal authorities in Prague.
The socialists had to explain the concepts of "Voldemort", "the biggest golf hole in Prague", "going to pastry", "bull neck", "betrayal of the capital" and "blinding".
Three councillors agreed to submit to the test and one fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will be responsible for the education in Prague in the future, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, directly refused to do so.
“I don’t get involved in these things and I don’t want to appreciate how civic Democrats have fun.”
“What matters to me is how we will behave in the execution of our programs,” he said.
As has been seen, Councilman Lukáš Kaucký allegedly would not have realized that the previous title is an expression of an influential entrepreneur and a friend of former mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
The word "Voldemort" says nothing to Kaucký; the only term he hit in the exam is "the largest golf hole in Prague".
"This is the Blanka tunnel," says Kaucký, who immediately adds: "But rather I know it from the news."
“I’m going to have to sign up for a language course,” she jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the Councillor of Environment Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both socio-Democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; in addition, he suspects the meaning of "going to the pastries".
"I think it means going to a Prague company"; soon Plachý is revealed that it is the headquarters of Janoušek companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge obtained them from the news, but he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the participants in the test, there is no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms among the socio-Democrats.
“I asked my colleagues, but it really seems like we don’t have anything like that.”
"Rather, among us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations, or we do word games with names," says the president of Prague's ČSSD, Petr Hulínský, whose partymates call Hulda.
“In school I was called Bříza, but I don’t know if my colleagues call me that too,” says his own nickname Karel Březina.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz tested the name and it works.
For his partymates, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they partnered before the elections deceptions during the party's sponsorship, is nicknamed "Igráček" ("playmobile") by some of his comrades.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that socio-Democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský doesn’t like being called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz even discovered other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The Doctor of the Rights of the Fucks" seems to recall that Petr Hulinský obtained his doctorate in law at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to limit torture of "witches," he published in a brochure
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually older, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who “return” witches are sent to an isolated area, so they don’t harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer this if not."
“Healthy young women are also not isolated, because they help in work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the state of West Africa, Burkina Faso, is occupied in a special residence of more than one hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual “social measure.”
He issued an informative brochure that should help to avoid witch hunting.
However, this has a stick.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso do not know how to read,” warns Die Standard about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighboring Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim it was due to a miserable cluster of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman burned herself in the oil used for ritual anointing.
It burned on when the group wanted to "expel evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devourers of human souls have always been a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government tries to appease witch hunting, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a broad hunt for witches that allegedly had been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic."
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forced men and women randomly chosen from among the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a portion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects which, in addition, caused them bowel and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay at the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about 1,000 detainees.
The tenant of Bakala: heated with coal stoves and signed a higher rental
The elderly and old man crossed the doors of RPG Byty’s customer service center of the “coal magnate” Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he had some documents with the new three-storey rental contracts: his, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving sentence.
All three have just seen the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the son will pay 4,100 crowns from next year for a two-room apartment with second-class separate kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when they will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, man only makes an ademan.
“Everybody says one thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a large laboratory for testing liberalization.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of apartments that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rental.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine o’clock, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to pick up number.
"Lease 2011", can be read on a light button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a small paper with a number comes out of the machine.
It hardly gives you time to read "157" and the number already appears on the big screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Shortly thereafter, an elderly marriage comes to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rents.
Most people come to solve regular problems, such as formerly: requests for settlements, insurance issues, and similar issues.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of tenants of most of the 44,000 RPG floors around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes a rental increase of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been working for a week, so it’s starting,” they answer, after briefly doubting the workers found in it when the client presents himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and the old Bakala mine floors are the most delicate issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were treated loudly and clearly by the Vice-President of Parliament, originating in Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now they are continuously appearing in the newspapers in the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"I didn't even change my damn bathroom dish," the man mentioned in the introduction unhungers.
According to the workers, at the moment retirees come more than anything to check if they get a discount on the rent if they sign in time, as the special RPG offer promises.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the February rental discount.
However, the window of mining “liberalization” certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rental in 2011 about forty or fifty people,” she estimates.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rental, an independent judge must resolve the matter.
“It’s not a threat, it’s information about the only possible way of proceeding and fully in accordance with the law,” RPG warns on its pages.
“You’re not going to judge anyone here,” says one of RPG employees Byty and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center gives her, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court,” he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait,” he says.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic need.
“The current rentals still don’t even cover the amounts necessary to maintain the community fund,” recalled Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, adding that the neglected state of the community fund that annoys tenants is, for owners, the main reason to increase the rent.
While during the five years that passed between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in rents in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.200 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that highlights red.
"The rental increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per month per square meter," the screen said.
It only increased the rental of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio by 38%.
“In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, 19.66 crowns per square meter,” RPG says.
At 2,600 flats, the rent will remain invariable next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not impact rents suddenly, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the hike of the rent (see the chart) back in the floors, mainly in saving in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rental increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare.
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with all the same to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees have been able to attend her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio numerous well-known buildings in Brno emerged, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guardroom.
About 90 people work at the company, mainly in the baby boom age, and they wanted to allow architects and delineators to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to its workers as part of its social program.
Builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of their children.
The mini-guardery was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-guard is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a staffing of more than 2.8 million Czech krones) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding (two years) runs out, the company Arch.Design has an obligation to maintain the mini-garden with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted for a year and the submission of the application for funding contributed to the company Economy Rating.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present throughout the day for their care. The nursery currently hosts children without age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-guardy", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of daycare is flexible to adapt to the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use daycare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-guardery program are comparable to the usual preschool program.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up late children from school when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened staff marketing.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of the stone, the tile and mosaic fragments, a façade reminiscent of the scales and the omnipresent softly curved lines, all are typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with onic lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought-out order is observed.
At night, the entire façade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the torsion of forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, railings, door ornaments, mirrors and signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample neighborhood at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gracia, emerged from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of carrying out a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, consisting of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
Architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their project plans arose ornaments for the representative apartment of the property owner and the mosaics used in the façade.
On the façade workers also other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and Gaudí’s Güell Park, where other parts of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion nicknamed it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of the worms."
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí projected in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their inclination of forty-five degrees may be strange.
During construction, Gaudí did not respect the construction rules of the moment at all and was not allowed to be influenced by them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although obviously the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so shocked by the result that it asked to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the town hall requested, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewellery.
The six-storey house is completely traversed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform were to break all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the lounges and a larger group can communicate in this way smoothly, without giving up the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and dashlights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on every floor of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which, on the contrary, absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded visits to the common area and the hallway, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and tourist card holders get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
