A survey that reveals ridiculous rules
The Absurdity Survey of the Year is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
He has already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity Survey of the Year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was taken by more than a third of the nearly 4,000 voters.
For example, the social security administration requested an excerpt from the trade register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech Social Security Administration will no longer ask for an excerpt from the trade register when it checks the insured's taxes," said ČSSZ spokeswoman Jana Buraňová.
The purpose of the Absurdity Survey of the Year is to consult the rules and regulations that companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic must respect and try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year forms part of the Hospodářské noviny business tournament for the fourth time and begins to create hobby among the general public as well.
While last year’s edition had the participation of 3,000 voters, it almost reached 4,000 this year.
And it is not surprising, since we still have several legal obligations that must be respected simply to trade.
“Perhaps in the number of papers needed for tax returns we are at the world’s first place,” says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, simplifying business standards has been a stated goal of all governments.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation is improving especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for having a company, Czechia is in position 74a, i.e. eight positions worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was held for the first time in 2006 and is repeated each year in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
The proposals can be made on the website www.firmaroku.cz. The organizer of the contest then selects seven candidates for the "anti-premium" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
It wins the absurdity that gets the most votes.
For this year’s survey more than a hundred were presented, in particular 105 meaningless rules and regulations.
The examples were sent by both entrepreneurs and professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the contest was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that entrepreneurs with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
This year’s list of seventy proposals is published on the pages of the competition.
The announcement of the competition, which always takes place at the beginning of November in Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world often participate.
This year, for example, the event was attended by Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
“Economic prosperity cannot be sustained if the state continually blocks entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate every year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade,” said Minister of Industry and Commerce Martin Kocourek.
Efforts to eliminate the absurd regulations are not left in burrow water.
In 2007, what disturbed people most was the obligation of the entrepreneur to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating zone, the intention to go with a position to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was removed in the new industrial law.
The obligation, which ended second in number of votes in 2007, i.e. the communication to the work office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the so-called green card law.
The third is the defeat.
The Absurdity of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their consultation a large mirror, a fridge and two floor scales.
This year, the Ministry of Health issued a statement saying it had eliminated the obligation to have a fridge.
