Families will have to pay additional expenses of several hundred crowns a month.
Since January, households will have to pay not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, larger rents.
Accordingly, families will have to take out of the portfolio, starting in January, several hundred crowns a month more than now.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, the gas roughly 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for the water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The rise in electricity for families living in apartments should rise to about 100 crowns more a year than now.
However, major electricity suppliers lowered prices, as support for energy production from renewable sources, particularly photovoltaic, has increased.
However, the gas is moderately increased, especially at the time when heating is most used and therefore higher consumption.
In this case, they should also have a couple hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are growing across the country, the price change of central heating varies from place to place.
The price rise is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay for central heating about 50 crowns more a month since January, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 crowns more a year.
Prague residents will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rental of infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, the Pragueans will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will continue to be among the lowest in the entire country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
The rental prices of 450,000 rented apartments in Prague can rise considerably, where regulation will end in January.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns in Ústí nad Labem around 2,500 flats, will increase rent from January to 100%.
The company will bring to court those who disagree with the new rent.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 flats, could increase by up to 10% next year.
Young Czechs get drunk with Fernet and rum. Beer is no longer in fashion, because it works slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in health care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hunger are no longer an exception.
This derives from the experience of physicians encountering such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
“Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get them drunk.”
“Now fashion is strong alcoholic beverages,” says Pravo, head of pediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Luděk Pelikán.
"When they manage to catch a bottle from their father's locker, it can be whisky, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Wodka has the advantage that it lightens with juice and doesn’t smell so much,” he explains.
This is confirmed by Motol University Hospital spokeswoman Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
"Those are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use spirits that they took at home," adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, it is 13 and 14-year-olds who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to go in perhaps four times."
"It started at the age of twelve, when she was brought with 3.5 alcohol in the blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy," said the department's doctor.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party."
“The interesting thing is that his mother wasn’t surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours,” the boss said.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance for drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of increased alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts note that, in the case of children, it is not possible to speak properly of dependence.
“Alcoholic is a person who has a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children.”
“In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it’s rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment,” explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, this year forty drunk children were hospitalized at the Motol Paediatric Clinic until mid-November.
However, the statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and should stay in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after walking medical examination, go home with their parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink spirits, there are three seasonal ups and downs to mention for Pelikán: Witch Day, New Year's Day and the end of school.
"In such circumstances, they drink for bad notes or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
“On the Witch Day I came to see up to seven drunk children at a time in admissions,” Pelikan adds.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hunger at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by injection of a serum with glucose and nutrients lacking in the body.
"These do it much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and don't hurt at all."
"They are only confused about where they are," says Pelikan, adding that patients often lose good mood at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
Ambulance transfer and hospitalization in a serious patient room cost tens of thousands of crowns.
“I’ve often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the kids directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a job for young people so that you would earn enough to pay that night,” Pelikán adds.
Health insurance, in your opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually returns people the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft found in foreign hands for the first time in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, by which the Czech Ministry of Defense replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, departed Tuesday to Seville, where the manufacturer of the aircraft Casa - EADS is located.
This is the first time that such a device has been found in the hands of someone other than the Czech army.
For the time being, they were only abroad for internship or demonstration flights.
This is the two-seater version L-159T1, which was so far used by the Czech army and was still in the state of flying.
The remaining three aircraft are the one-seat L-159.
These are still kept in Aer Vodochody and the sales intermediary, the company Omnipol, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peješk, of the defense press department, says it is not yet known when the planes will be physically withdrawn from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seat aircraft, instead, were separated from the long-repaired aircraft, with no additional investments or contributions from the Ministry."
"The L-159T1 two-seaters were exchanged in their current state," he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army does not run out of two-seat planes, since in May 2009 the army signed with Aer Vodochody a contract for a total of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary two-seat L-159 devices.
One of the new aircraft was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS pledged that the aircraft will be added to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly states that EADS is the company that withdraws the L-159 aircraft and will serve for pilot practices from NATO countries."
“It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how he will use them in this framework,” says Pejšek.
The Hospodářské noviny newspaper published earlier that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defense did not convene a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense management states that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159 abroad.
The Czech army acquired from Aer 72 aircraft and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa planes may have judicial consequences.
The European Commission has already reported to the Czech Ministry of Defense before the European Court of Justice because it should choose aircraft by conducting a European tender and not contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the latter is expected to arrive at Prague’s Kbely airport in fourteen days.
A longer index finger than the annular indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longer index than annular are subject to a lower risk of suffering from prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer magazine.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
“Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple proof of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Thus, the finger could help determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, particularly if this feature is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, Eeles indicates.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the finger pointer of the right hand shorter than the annular finger.
They had the same chances of suffering from prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
For men with a longer index than the annular finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that he does not think that the relationship between the length of the fingers and cancer can be "completely demonstrated".
