An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new forms of life on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new forms of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it demonstrates that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
“This body has a double capacity.”
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
“That makes it very peculiar, although it’s little left to be a really ‘alien’ way of life,” said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in Thursday’s online edition of the publication Science.
It has long been considered that there are six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“It makes you wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on different planets from Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated large speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery “yes shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of “standard” elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed,” said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and the basic biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on Monkey Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could substitute one for another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"Consequently, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn't work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, so to speak, appeals to biochemical machinery," explains Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbe grows best with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead poses the possibility that a form of life that uses arsenic may naturally exist, either in other parts of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an auxiliary professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found to prove that it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth ages, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
“Yes, it suggests that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in ancient times,” Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team, said.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
