Prosecutors will not bring charges against Senator Ensign
Senator’s lawyers announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have excused Senator John Ensign for criminal charges that arose from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure lobby work for the wife’s husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat faced by Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair had national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said he was "surely happy" with the decision, which came after an entire year investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary measure by the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Department of Justice had “informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of his investigation and has no plan to raise charges against him on this issue.”
The Justice Department did not want to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise for many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign could have confabulated to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
Interviews, email, and other documents first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative lobby work, to achieve Hampton and his wife, Cynthia,'s silence about the senator's affair with her.
Ms. Hampton once worked as a treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr. Hampton and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an Ensign assistant, he was excluded under the law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared to disagree with the so-called “revolving door lobbying ban”, which seeks to restrict former state employees using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it seemed to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute," said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department seemed cautious about accepting political prosecutions after several important setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year’s decision to quit the prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, amid misconduct charges.
Federal prosecutors “are clearly cowards,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
“This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them,” he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s chief lawyer, said in an interview he received a phone call from a Justice Department attorney on Monday and another further call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to raise charges against his client.
Ensign’s defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to prosecutors.
“I don’t feel comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say we thought they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to change an investigation into a complaint separated by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign's parents to the Hamptons violated federal electoral law.
The electoral commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was nothing but a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, which got lobby work thanks to the help Ensign gave Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign’s chief of staff John Lopez contacted Hampton and told him that he was “madding” the Interior Ministry on a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and called the transportation secretary to establish a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When the news of the affair first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his voters and resigned from his position as fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign spokeswoman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, he said the senator expected the ethics committee to swiftly follow the example of the Department of Justice and conclude its investigation.
“Senator Ensign has a desire to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada,” he said.
