They observed in a rejection of the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media continually threw wood into the fire of emotion about the case.
“Daily crowded media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the court,” the lawyers wrote, “was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps throughout the state.”
Her attention to Tweeter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said the complaint that immediate news was more important than the reports delivered more slowly, was a ludicrous vision that would make the court’s policy on coverage control weak in future proceedings.
But some lawyers said appeal courts were often attracted to the arguments about adaptation required in court due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pushing for that claim.
In their writing, they referred to the Supreme Court’s 1966 decision, which revoked Dr. Sheppard’s conviction due to the coverage of the trial, and made clear that they would demand that new media would require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the 21st century Sheppard vs. Maxwell case."
Can civicism build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiveness and negativity, this week a bit of civicism has been triggered in Washington.
Is it a premonition of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues that should be addressed during the outgoing session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the remaining political differences between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Both sides are now in a trial period, surveying each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed party war.
Reason for which the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent assessments by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are in opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed regarding how things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
The elections awaken partisan passions, which then extinguish.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment allowances, probably because Republicans can’t make them believe they are in favor of tax cuts for the wealthy, denying unemployment allowance for unemployed workers.
Following Tuesday’s White House meeting, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuing bipartisanism when the new 112nd Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things to be done are done, psychology will in the short term reverse the situation to a confrontation,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and cancel the new health law.
Those support lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission ' s recommendations, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the cutting of expenditure.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken care of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forced the question of the deficit into the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected panel officials, suggesting that in tax matters there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will take place next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama over budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would the change cause?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanness of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as it happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they are losing will probably change course and seek engagement.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are now bigger than they were in the mid-1990s, and there appears to be a bigger ideological gap between Obama and Congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find points in common on the issues that still divide them.
