Red Khmer veterans forced to face the past
In a weakly illuminated concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Red Khmer Ta Mok.
"Here everyone loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he cared about his people," said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge rule, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Khmer surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally being challenged at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly face people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook here that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a United Nations-Cambodian mixed court issued the first sentence of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentenced the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Red Khmer of Anlong Veng, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Red Khmers, but they can do nothing,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
“To them, life under the Red Khmer was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
“This is generating divisions within families.”
During the Cambodian Red Khmer rule, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, illness or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government, the remains of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of Western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Red Khmer fighters began to desert towards government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while waiting for the trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Red Khmer fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few Red Khmer elite officials retained their local administrative positions in exchange for laying down their weapons, rough soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
“These people have gained little after surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They have incorporated the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime.”
“They were raised without any concept to do business.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Red Khmers when he was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
“Life with the Red Khmer was fine,” he said.
"Ta Mok fed everyone."
“But now life is difficult because we have to self-supply ourselves.”
The current Khmer Rouge court has also caused concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Red minister.
The court’s mandate is to prosecute leading leaders and those with greater responsibility for crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases in addition to those four.
This did not serve much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Red Khmer rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodian Documentation Center that she had supervised the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers are believed to have died.
During a recent stunning afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden piles on a ground road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun threw long shadows over the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Red Khmers.
She said that if the court called her, she would not appear.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," he said.
“If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who deserted from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question him.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is precisely what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
“Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to re-unite the broken pieces,” he said.
“It is our duty to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Red Khmers, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed on Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the high school history textbook of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Red Khmers.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little about the Red Khmer, despite the city’s bond with the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he took the book home to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court,” he said.
“They have suspicions because they are unsure about how many people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the process of reconciliation complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Red Khmer retains a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a path with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a black soot rectangle covered by a oxidized canned roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a bunch of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone salesman on the edge of the road, said he didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
