Finally, the UEFA discipline committee has sanctioned the team’s coach José Mourinho with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or the like is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written but followed by this sport.
Part of the debate arising in the reported case is because it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and which has occasionally fined its players for similar acts) and the drama orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds an episode more to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulations contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether with these actions fraud of law is committed; because, indeed, they are actions respectful of the sports regulations, but they seem to circumvent their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of harm they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the goods that sports spirit comprises is the physical integrity of opposing players, aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these goods referred to in fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
However, the paradoxical thing about the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as a trap or fraud of law, because their violation of the rules was not done hiddenly to try to avoid the penalty, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious thing to receive the punishment of the arbitrator.
They looked forward to and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders get in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not placed in disadvantage or gained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it’s not a useful strategy for the next game either, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, as the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this performance the players fulfil a penalty game and move to the second card cycle, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, going through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sports spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor the most of what the rules allow.
In the case we are concerned, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without running out of the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, I think this time it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises by two factors: because it was about two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the guideline was carried out to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so ethical as aesthetic.
