US changes rules to obtain a visa
Individuals will have to go to the Visa Applicants Service Centers before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa will be changed at the U.S. Embassy and consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to Visa Applicants Service Centers (ASC) before their interview with the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, you will no longer need to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application, and another one for the courier to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including visa for temporary workers) and $390 for visa for merchants and investors.
People wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this section less time than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
