450 million in contracts without tenders
Hydro-Québec has awarded direct contracts worth $450 million to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the center of this avalanche of more than one hundred contracts is a consortium formed by the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained without a prior tender the most important contract, the project management, for a sum of 295 million.
The consortium, called Énergie Gérance, was created in 2004 following Hydro-Québec’s decision to entrust the private sector with its responsibility to manage this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
At the beginning of 2005, the Energy Gérance consortium obtained the lucrative contract without a prior public tender.
For the Quebec Party, the use of corporate consortia poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and cause a price rise.
“This is a new method of collusion and eliminating competition.”
“I mean, people, instead of doing it secretly, now do it openly,” Sylvain Simard, a member of the Party, said in a press conference yesterday.
Earlier in the morning, Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because, he says, he does not understand how the public interest can be benefited in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, firmly denying that there was a collusion with this contract.
"I'm starting to get tired," he protested, arguing that the PQ had acted "dishonestly" and "lack of rigor."
He noted that “the minimum” would be for the PQ to apologize.
The consortium formula is a common practice throughout the world.
Typically, it is an alliance with a time limit that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project presents a high level of complexity, taking into account the magnitude of the works.
The works have already started and will last until 2012.
In any case, the contract has been awarded without competition; it has been negotiation.
In addition, the consortium formula has ceased to be the exception to the standard in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir published last week, the consortium formula in the technical advice sector is being investigated by the Government.
A quick look at Quebec’s merchant record allows you to identify more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
In this way, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal person, that is, Dessau.
With regard to the Energy Gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau has stressed that "the territory of James Bay responds to a particular labor dynamic and Hydro-Québec specifically responds to it since the 1970s."
The great Eastmain project manager, Réal Laporte, of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has given an explanation highlighting the fact that the project management contract has been awarded directly.
“If you respond to a tender and there are few participants, your prices will be higher.”
“You have two options: you can get in touch with the sector’s actors and tell them: we’re going to negotiate a satisfactory deal with a good price.”
"However, the idea is that what matters is not the price, but the competition of people," Laporte said.
The contract awarded to the Energy Gérance consortium is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Quebec Party.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or the SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
Following the verification, Le Devoir identified 109 technical advisory contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to companies or their subsidiaries, in particular geotechnical laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has obtained 22 contracts, Génivar obtained 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, without taking into account its stake in Énergie gérance.
All contracts were negotiated.
In total, it amounts to $449,783,344, including the energy management contract of $295.131,564.
Sylvain Simard has suggested that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "good known of the Liberal Party of Quebec."
Minister Normandeau has dropped that the PQ is also linked to these companies, which "finance" it, before specifying that it is rather about its leaders.
Responsible consumption barometer. The "green" label does not inspire confidence
More ecological, but deeply skeptical.
The Canadian consumer hardly trusts the actors of sustainable development, as well as fair trade brands or ecological certificates to guide their choices.
According to the Responsible Consumption Barometer, whose first results were published yesterday, the situation is even worse. The consumer is immersed in a media universe where they pull messages that advocate for more responsible consumption, but regrets the lack of reliable information and considers it even curbs their commitment.
Even though consumption of products called “socially responsible” has increased in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those trying to sell them.
Two-thirds of them say they do not trust the environmental commitment of companies or the environmental advertising of them, reveals the measuring tool developed by the Responsible Consumer Observatory of the University of Sherbrooke.
Another conclusion: half of consumers doubt the reliability of official certificates that carry products called fair, as well as the credibility of products and brands that carry labels indicating that they are "ecoresponsible," the Barometer notes.
Similarly, only 14.6% of the Quebecers take the speeches of politicians on this issue seriously.
In any case, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this consumption sector, which is currently supported by nearly a third of consumers in Belgium.
In fact, gaps and the dubious nature of information cause 46% of consumers to dismiss this option.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the highest price of these products.
In addition, a third of the Quebecers say they also distrust the supposed yields of the ecological products or services they are trying to sell.
On the other hand, almost half of consumers changed their habits in 2010 and, especially, changed the brand of one or more products to respect their beliefs.
61% have given priority to shopping in their neighborhood stores and have preferred to buy food products grown in their region, the Barometer notes.
More green and responsible (the responsible consumption index has reached 64 points out of a maximum of 100 this year), Quebec’s Homo consumus loves to occupy the position of recycling king trying to reduce its impact on the environment by worrying about the protection of wildlife.
However, according to the Barometer, that social awareness seems to be doors (from his car) outside: in 2010, only 28% of Quebecers indicated that they have used public transport or shared car to defend their environmental principles.
In addition, 39.1% of participants in this extensive behavior survey, which has just completed its first edition, supports the use of bicycles and walking.
A loan for the State to recover eXcentris
The Government of Quebec, which has been asked to commit itself financially to the recovery of the cinema complex eXcentris after the Société Angus and the Parallèle, agrees to collaborate, but only through a loan.
The Société de développement Angus and the Parallèle, who expected a donation of seven million dollars from the Ministry of Culture to buy Daniel Langlois the film complex eXcentris at Saint-Laurent Boulevard and return to him his true cinéphile vocation, have not obtained what they asked.
The Government has agreed to be involved in the matter, but under its own conditions.
Instead of the expected donation, the Government of Quebec proposes a loan which would in fact be less than initial expectations; it could constitute a viable solution under advantageous conditions, at least in the opinion of certain public employees.
Quebec had already rejected a first plan of action and a request of 12.8 million last spring, but since then applications have been revised downwards.
The president of the Société de développement des entreprises culturelles (SODEC), François Macerola, who leads the eXcentris file, submitted a proposal and an action plan to the Minister St-Pierre.
He sent him a last report a dozen days ago.
However, SODEC received a counter-proposal from the cabinet on Tuesday.
The Parallele and Angus have a deadline until 31 December to respond to the same.
In any case, it seems that the hypothesis of a State donation should be completely dismissed.
Remember that the Association of Owners of Cinema and Film Complexes in Quebec opposed a direct investment by the State to support the recovery of eXcentris, arguing that the Ministry of Culture should not finance real estate projects, since it has not done so with other cinemas.
On the other hand, various representatives of the sector are calling for considerable economic aid.
Daniel Langlois, the owner of the resort, has been carrying the burden of author cinema at its premises for ten years, after financing its own construction, which could justify a revocation by the Treasury Council.
The lack of rooms for independent films is evident in Montreal and eXcentris had managed to loyalty to its clients.
The company Angus and Parallele, led by Christian Yaccarini, are pursuing a private funding campaign, hoping to raise $700,000 to make their way to the acquisition.
Since spring 2009, only one of these rooms, the Parallele, continues to screen films on eXcentris.
The aim of the future buyers is to reopen the three rooms on February 27, screening Xavier Beauvois's precious film "Des hommes et des dieux".
However, Christian Yaccarini has not contacted Le Devoir again and we do not know what he and his group think of the downside proposals they have received.
The veil of Canada is lifted...
The new U.S. diplomatic cables released by WikiLeaks uncover what the U.S. considers the Canadians’ complex with respect to Americans, but at the same time reflects the latter’s feeling of superiority towards Canada.
U.S. diplomats are surprised that Canadian voters don’t think about Canada-U.S. relations when they are going to vote and believe that President Obama’s visit has helped the conservative government get its budget approved in 2009!
The four new communications between the U.S. embassy in Ottawa and Washington that were made public yesterday, offer rather juicy details than really substantial content.
A cable dated September 22, 2008, that is, during the full federal election campaign, reports on the extent to which the United States does not enter into the issues discussed by political leaders.
This caused great surprise to the U.S. ambassador sent to Ottawa, David Wilkins.
Mr Wilkins gives some explanations about this situation.
“Perhaps political leaders are conditioned by a complex of virtually inherent inferiority to Canadians when dealing with daily domestic issues, rather than leaving such an election to the United States (as during the 1988 free trade campaign),” he writes.
Accordingly, the United States is "the proverbial elephant of this choice: ubiquitous, but potentially too dangerous to speak of it."
The ambassador has even more difficulty understanding this "deceitful silence" because the two countries maintain intense political and economic relations.
“Logically, he thinks, the ability of a candidate, a party, and even more, the party leader to manage these essential relationships should be a key factor that voters should think about when voting.”
This feeling of importance can also be seen in the cable sent on January 22, 2009 by Terry Breese, head of business in Ottawa, to prepare President Barack Obama for his first visit to Ottawa.
“His journey will help ensure the government’s survival during the vote of trust in early February on the federal budget, through which Canada will register for the first time a deficit in the last decade due to a recovery plan of between $30 billion and $40 billion,” Mr. Breese wrote.
Nowhere is mentioned that the government had to extend the parliament before Christmas to prevent the coalition from being replaced or that opposition parties conditioned its survival on the quality of the proposed recovery plan.
Another January 2008 communication signed by Ambassador Wilkins warns Washington about the increasingly negative image transmitted by the dramatic series broadcast on the U.S. CBC.
The ambassador is concerned about the broadcast of Border, Little Mosque on the Prairie, Intelligence and H2O, in which unsubtle references are made to Maher Arar, the "No-Fly-List" or even to the kidnappings for the CIA to conduct vigorous interrogations.
Another cable reports that during her first bilateral meeting, Hillary Clinton asked her French counterpart Bernard Kouchner if Europe would be willing to welcome some Guantanamo prisoners.
Mr. Kouchner replied yes, but that it depended "on each case".
At the end of the meeting, they wrote "he has handed over a document to the Secretary of State in connection with Omar Khadr, a 15-year-old Muslim of Canadian origin."
"The Secretary agreed to review the file."
Finally, we can mention that the moods in relation to the WikiLeaks site have warmed up.
Tom Flanagan, a former counselor very close to Stephen Harper, said on CBC radio that the person responsible for this mass escape should be "killed."
In the United States they echo Mike Huckabee.
A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by an amount that corresponds to virtually one-third of the additional decrease to be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of concrete major projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to offset the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopoly between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluo-compact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED"), much of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major issuer countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, pledged to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, further 5 Gt of that amount should be reduced to stabilize, by 2020, the rise in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluo-compact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is reduced even twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostates and emit very little heat.
Above, they contain nothing mercury.
Several specialists have expressed their reservations regarding fluocompact bulbs, as they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report notes, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not fluo-compact bulbs, but coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce electricity waste with the incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury a year.
The report outlines the advantages that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would save itself $1 billion a year in electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
Ivory Coast looks forward to announcement of election results
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has requested the "immediate" publication of the results of the presidential election in Côte d'Ivoire, as the deadlines have expired.
“The Secretary-General highlights the need for the independent electoral commission to complete its work and announce the provisional results immediately,” a spokesman for the UN chief said.
“Ask all Ivory Coast parties and institutions to demonstrate their sense of responsibility and refrain from any initiative until the provisional results are announced.”
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the electoral commission has allowed the deadline on Wednesday to midnight without the results being published, three days after Sunday’s scrutiny.
About forty minutes before the deadline ended, the CIS president had told television that the committee “continued working” to announce the results.
On Wednesday, the requests for the CIS to finally proclaim the name of the winner of the second round between the outgoing Laurent Gbagbo and his opponent Alassane Ouattara have multiplied in the world.
However, the Gbagbo side has been annulled by the Constitutional Council of the "fraudulent" votes in the north, in the hands of the former New Forces (NF) rebellion since the failed coup in September 2002.
Pascal Affi N'Guessan, head of the campaign of the president of Ivory Coast, said the intimidation manoeuvres of voters carried out by the FN in the north of the country had dissuaded the followers of the outgoing president from going to vote.
The entire election could be void if the Constitutional Council accepts the complaints filed by Gbagbo.
However, Gbagbo’s opponents consider that the country’s highest court is not neutral, as it is led by Paul Yao N’Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, a Northern man who deny any relationship with the former rebels, has judged the delay in publication of the results "unacceptable" and has asked Gbagbo to respect them, but has not gone as far as to claim victory.
His allies claim that Gbagbo blocks the publication of the results because he knows he has lost and that it would be illegal to file a complaint with the Constitutional Council after preventing the electoral commission from disseminating the results.
The second round of the presidential elections on Sunday should have put the grid on the process of reunification and reconciliation of a country divided into two for years.
The United Nations on Wednesday warned the political class in Ivory Coast that they could be held responsible for possible acts of violence.
Laurent Gbagbo had finished in the first round on October 31 with 38% of the votes versus 32% of Alassane Ouattara, who publicly received the support of former President Henri Konan Bédié (25% in the first round).
Unemployment rate remains stable in France in the third quarter
According to the International Labour Organization (ILO), the unemployment rate in France has remained stable at 9.3% in continental territory (9.7% taking into account overseas departments), as indicated by data corrected with provisional seasonal variations (CVE) published Thursday by the Insee.
The number of unemployed remains at 2,631,000 in mainland France.
The second quarter data have been confirmed, 9.3% of the working population in continental territory and 9.7% with DOMs.
In a year, the unemployment rate has risen by 0.1 points.
Overall, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France were not working in the third quarter, but want to work, whether or not available within two weeks to work and whether they are looking for work or not.
The situation of young people present in the labour market has continued to worsen, with a further increase in the unemployment rate to 24.2% in mainland France (+0.9 points in three months, +0.5 points in a year), 25% including DOMs.
During the third quarter, 637,000 young people between the ages of 15 and 24 were unemployed in the sense of the ILO.
For its part, there has been a slight increase in unemployment among the elderly, up to 6.4% in mainland France (+0.2 points in both three months and one year), i.e. 482,000 people over 50 years of age, which amounts to 6.6% with DOMs.
Only unemployment stability has been recorded among people between the ages of 25 and 49, with 8.3% in mainland France (-0.1 points in three months, +0.1 points in a year) and 8.8% in all France.
The Insee has been without publication of the monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversy about its methods of calculation.
Eurostat, the European Union’s statistics agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a 9.8% rate for France (DOM included) in October, after 9.9% in September.
Alexandre Guérini investigated and arrested
Alexandre Guérini, 53, director of waste treatment companies and brother of the President PS of the General Council of Bouches-du-Rhône, is being investigated and has been imprisoned in the Luynes prison near Aix-en-Provence, in the context of an investigation into allegedly fraudulent public procurement.
Alexandre Guérini is being investigated for abuse of social property, misuse of funds and public property, cover-up, active corruption, trafficking in influences and possession of ammunition, his lawyer said.
"Alexandre Guérini will fight and answer all the questions the magistrate poses to him, not ghosts."
“It’s easy to persecute him for a multitude of reproachable acts, another thing is to prove them,” her lawyer, Florence Rault, told AFP before her client’s appearance.
Mr. Guérini, brother of the PS leader in the department, Jean-Noël Guérini, has wanted to transmit through his lawyers to the judge, before his appearance, a document to explain himself.
On Wednesday evening they began investigating and imprisoned one of their close people, Philippe Rapezzi.
According to his lawyer, Mr. Lucien Simon, the only thing his client has done has been to take care of the landfills he has to manage.
As to the allocation of contracts or the destination of funds related to their execution, he knows nothing about it, says lawyer Simon.
In the context of this file, Daniel Pinna, former director general of the services of the urban agglomeration of Aubagne, is also being investigated since Wednesday, for misuse of funds and complicity, but he has been left probationally and is prohibited from meeting with the protagonists of the case.
"My client has been able to explain all the facts that have reproached him."
"The instructor magistrate has taken account of the explanations and has released him," said his lawyer, Mr. Yann Arnoux.
On the night of Tuesday to Wednesday, four other people were interrogated and left free, under judicial control in the case of two of them, according to the deputy prosecutor of the Republic, Michel Raffin.
Michel Karabadjakian, deputy director general of the property of Marseille Provence Métropole (MPM), has been charged with “trafficking in influences and passive corruption.”
Two officials in Aubagne’s township, Michèle Duval and Christophe Bringuier, have been interrogated for “restraining and misuse of public goods by a person dedicated to public service” and for “complicity in misuse of public funds”, respectively.
Finally, Alexandre Guérini’s partner, Jeannie Peretti, is being investigated for “covering abuse of social property.”
Among those who have faced Mr Guérini is Stéphane Brunengo-Girard, who was recently imprisoned in a parallel case of fraudulent public procurement affecting Corsica.
Investigators suspect their societies have served to launder the capital of great banditism.
The investigation is being conducted within the framework of several judicial instructions initiated against X in April 2009 following the receipt of anonymous communications, of course fraud in the allocation of public procurement, in particular in the waste sector.
A source close to the investigation notes that the investigations focus especially on the conditions of allocation and operation of a landfill in La Ciotat, which collects waste from Aubagne, as well as from other cities in the urban community of Marseille (MPM).
Clotilde Reiss: The Elisha has exaggerated Syria’s mediation
For more than ten months, between July 2009 and May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher detained in Iran for "espionage", has been on the public in France, has warned of diplomacy and has accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the attentive eyes of U.S. diplomats.
American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal certain unknown aspects of this crisis.
They describe how the Elisha has explained its strategy to Americans to the point of giving them advice on how to manage their own “hostage” crisis in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials tried to convince Washington that the release of the young French woman did not come in exchange for the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and sought by US justice for trafficking in materials for the Iranian nuclear program.
Finally, they reveal the crude reality of how the French presidency tried to manipulate the media to give the idea that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad had played an essential role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
Actually, he didn't do anything.
A diplomatic telegram drafted on August 12, 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French commentary on how to manage hostage-taking cases".
The Elisee counselor for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, talk to U.S. diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method.
They advise Americans to do the following to repatriate their own forcibly detained citizens in Iran.
“Make noise,” they say, “continuously release” in the media the words “fundamental human rights,” “innocence,” “immediate release.”
All to shame the Iranian regime, careful of its image.
“When the Iranians ask you to stop, do it even more frequently.”
Because, once the attempts to negotiate through discrete channels are exhausted, “silence will solve nothing,” the Iranians are “experts in delaying manoeuvres.”
Mr. Richier adds that the detention of foreigners is “a usual Iranian tactic: the taking of hostages for political blackmail.”
He announced that the release of Clotilde Reiss from prison (which will take place on August 16, the day she will take refuge in the French embassy) "will require a large amount of money to be granted to Iranians" (€230,000 in reward).
Furthermore, he notes that the Elisha anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that “will increase.”
The Iranians could “in the near future arrest another of the nearly 1,800 French citizens living in Iran,” he says.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss is released from prison after 12 days but is blocked in Iran.
The following information is disseminated: Iranian Majid Kakavand, whose extradition is requested by the United States for illicit trafficking in sensitive electronic material to Iran, has been released in Paris on a judge’s decision.
The U.S. Embassy, like many observers, doubt this strange coincidence.
For Washington, which closes Iran’s clandestine networks for procurement of material for the nuclear program, the release of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Has France accepted an exchange?
Releasing the Iranian in exchange for the French?
During a new conversation with Kathleen Allegrone, on September 4, François Richier assures that it wasn’t so.
The Elisha, he says, not only "has been enormously surprised by the judge's decision", but has tried to oppose it.
"There have been intense negotiations between the French presidency and the Minister of Justice" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government cannot cancel the judicial decision," he said.
Mr. Richier also wants to demonstrate that Majid Kakavand remains under the "strict" surveillance of French intelligence services.
The counselor of the Elisha marks a phone number, hangs and then informs the U.S. diplomat that the Iranian “is currently in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian embassy.”
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elisha spares no effort, uses media-organized communiqués and “leaks” to make believe that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad plays a “important” and “influential” role as a “mediator.”
Americans observe this activity with some irony and verify that the manipulation bears its fruits, since several newspaper articles broadcast the official French version.
A telegram dated August 25, 2009 mentions "the media 'blitz' of French officials."
What is the reason for such “gratitude” to Mr. Assad, the embassy in Paris wonders.
“Despite their praising statements, French officials acknowledge in private that they only have a vague idea of what the Syrians have actually done.”
Then the document deals with the reasons that have led Elisha to give rise to this fiction.
The major communication effort “is aimed at validating Sarkozy’s policy of openness towards Syria,” he says.
A policy initiated in 2008, which "in the opinion of numerous critical voices in France and abroad, had just been spotted of premature and undeserved."
By “exaggerating the Syrian role,” Paris tries to “show Syria the praise it can reap if it plays a constructive role in the region.”
The goal is also to “sow the seed of discord between Syria and Iran.”
The U.S. Embassy knows this from a good source.
On August 11, François Richier entrusted him: "Of course, we don't know if the Syrians have done anything or not."
"But anyway, we thanked him."
“At least, this should cause confusion among Iranians.”
Clotilde Reiss returns to France on May 16, 2010.
Nicolas Sarkozy receives her at the Eliseus.
In a statement, he thanked the presidents of Brazil, Senegal and Sirio for playing an “active role in the liberation of our compatriot.”
Starting at midnight, Korean youth can’t play online
The South Korean government is going to pass a law called Cinderella that will prevent teenagers from playing online games after midnight by blocking their access, government officials said.
In December, a bill will be submitted to Parliament to ask online gaming companies to block access to these games after midnight for young people under the age of 16, according to representatives from the Ministries of Culture and Family.
“A lot of kids play all night, and then they find it difficult to study in school and lead a normal life during the day.”
“We think this law is necessary to protect your health and your right to sleep,” said Jo Rin, a ministerial officer in charge of the bill.
Online games will be available again at 6 a.m.
Companies will have one year to prepare for law enforcement, precisely.
The government is also considering asking companies to limit the daily access time to these games when the parents of the young people so request, he added.
Furthermore, it will make free software available to anyone requesting that allows limiting the time of Internet connection.
South Korea is one of the most "connected" countries and newspapers regularly report on various facts related to intensive internet usage.
The country is also the undisputed champion of the world online gaming competitions.
In November, South Korea won four gold medals at the World Cyber Games, where it faced 58 other countries.
World Cup 2018-2022: FIFA appoints organizing countries
In the midst of the storm caused by suspicion of corruption, the FIFA executive committee on Thursday appoints the countries organizing the 2018 and 2022 World Cups, a clearly political election where influence struggles and lobbying can come to prevail over technical criteria.
One thing is clear, the 2018 edition of the FIFA competition will be held in Europe, traditional bastion of discipline (four candidates: England, Russia, Spain-Portugal and the Netherlands-Belgium).
The 2022 edition will be much more exotic, given that the International Federation expects to conquer new territories (Qatar, Australia), after a premiere on the African continent in 2010, or to continue its implantation in the United States or in the Far East (Japan, South Korea).
The list of personalities that were part of the delegations (David Cameron, Prince William, José Luis Rodriguez Zapatero, José Socrates, Bill Clinton, the emir of Qatar, the Belgian and Dutch heads of government, Zidane, Beckham, Cruyff) testifies to the economic and political interests at stake in a World Cup.
Behind-scenes transactions, therefore, may last until the last minute.
Furthermore, it is difficult to establish a hierarchy among candidates.
According to the FIFA evaluation report, English, Spanish-Portuguese (2018) and American (2022) nominations have better arguments than their competitors.
However, these considerations will not be too weighty for the 22 members of the executive committee when voting.
The Sunday Times, responsible for the revelations that led to the corruption suspension of two EC members (Reynald Temarii and Amos Adamu), could have ruined the opportunities of his country, the cradle of football, which only hosted the World Cup once, in 1966.
The BBC added wood to the burning on Monday by broadcasting a documentary that has highlighted three influential EC members, Ricardo Teixeira, Nicolas Leoz and Issa Hayatou.
Enough to dismay FIFA and embarrass British officials, who have launched intense lobbying in recent weeks with David Cameron heading.
The Chief of Government hopes to re-edit the successful blow by his predecessor, Tony Blair, who had managed to organize the J.O.O. 2012 for London in 2005.
Will this intense activity be enough to regain the brightness of England before the EC?
It is unclear, since the duo Spain-Portugal also has numerous strengths thanks to their stadiums, already ready, their experience (Mundial of 82 in Spain, JJ.OO in Barcelona in 1992, European Cup in 2004 in Portugal) and their football culture.
However, the shady economic and financial prospects of both countries could undermine their ambitions.
The possible retaliations against the English and the doubts about the solvency of Spain and Portugal all they manage is to give points to Russia, converted into a weighty outsider despite the gaps in their candidacy (stadions, hotels, transportation).
However, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin decided not to move to Zurich and has denounced an "unfair competition in the preparation of the vote", in a direct reference to the English press' allegations against EC members.
“They are shining their dirty cloths, trying to compromise them,” Putin said.
By 2022, the United States, which has the experience of 1994, seems to be the most logical favorites.
The world’s leading economic power and home to FIFA’s top sponsors, the country seems to be taking advantage of Japan and South Korea, which have developed an excellent project separately.
However, these new applications seem premature for two countries that organized the championship together in 2002.
Another risk: the 2026 World Cup grant to China, fervently desired by FIFA, which would cause Asia to go out of chance by 2022.
Alongside Qatar, which has presented its project based on futuristic stadiums, and Australia, FIFA would continue its expansion to new horizons, but both countries present more risks than certainty.
Australia, like Japan and Korea, could also be hurt by the weakness of TV fees paid (depending on the time difference) by European countries, the backbone of the war for FIFA.
Second mandate: the test
