Euro: ECB is forced to maintain its acquisitions of State Letters
The last meeting of the Council of Governors of the European Central Bank (ECB) of the year should allow to clarify the ways of exiting the crisis or at least announce the interruption of a large number of unconventional monetary policy operations that should end at the end of the year.
Due to the European sovereign debt crisis, the Frankfurt issuing institute will certainly not be able to afford to be so perennial if it does not want to risk aggravating a more than complicated situation today in the European bond markets.
The political cost would be equally high.
During a press conference yesterday, French Finance Minister Christine Lagarde supported the active role played by the ECB in resolving the European debt crisis.
It did not mean whether it considered that the central bank should do more, for example by increasing its purchasing program of state bonds.
“I reserve my opinion for my fellow Europeans.”
On the eve of his hearing before the European Parliament’s Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs, ECB President Jean-Claude Trichet did not show more eloquent in terms of his intentions, merely indicating that the secondary market State Letters purchase program “continued” and that “we will see what we decided” at Thursday’s meeting.
The only thing that is clear is that the ECB will keep its main rate invariable at 1%, the lowest level in its history since May 2009.
In practice, the ECB’s acquisition of Treasury bonds has doubled last week to nearly €1.35 billion.
Moreover, according to indiscrete market operators, he would have bought Irish and Portuguese bonds again yesterday.
In total, the central banks of the Eurosystem have acquired securities for an amount of EUR 67 billion since May 2010.
Among market operators, there is no doubt that purchases will continue (see page 29).
Economists also do not anticipate any significant changes in course.
Although loan operations longer than three months have already disappeared from the ECB’s arsenal, it still makes unlimited liquidity allocations at beneficial conditions and with duration ranging from one week to three months.
Economists expect this device to be extended for a few months today.
“I don’t think he’s going to modify his program considerably.”
“If not, it would be at risk of causing new tensions in the short term,” says Michael Schubert, economist at Commerzbank.
"It seems more likely that a progressive exit announced during the first quarter of 2011 will occur," says Norbert Bräms, economist at Sal.
Oppenheim.
