Revenge hackers and diligent spies
WikiLeaks has a double value.
On the one hand, it unveils an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems to be scandalized by the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and anticipates a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has taken a long time to give ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule according to which secret records should only be formed by news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosacruz) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those engaged in occultism not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know, editor of Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sending the U.S. embassy to the State Department was the same as the Newsweek published last week.
So why have the revelations of these records caused such a revolt?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of State can call by phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become spying centers.
Any spectator who watches research movies knows it perfectly, we just appear that we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad picture of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country significantly affects the State Department’s prestige.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the “verdicts.”
But let’s get into the true nature of what has happened.
Anciently, in Orwell’s time, he could be conceived of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape a hacker’s control, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power stand that can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty, unsecret secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets.
WikiLeaks hasn’t hurt Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and a lot, Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that in the future States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, as it would be like publishing it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it is also obvious that, with current technologies, we cannot expect to keep confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the time being, my prospect is a science fiction and therefore a novel, but I can imagine government agents who travel discreetly in diligence with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned out of memory or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: ultimately, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology now progresses like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph (telephone).
The (analog) videotapes had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, i.e. to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel involved, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
A last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly plotted at the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s shortcomings in its financing pledges
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked financing pledges (fast start or early calls) made by developed countries have been fulfilled.
And the French dips have been unveiled.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million a year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The operation transparency resulted in appreciation and was appreciated for what was really worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on the right track toward meeting its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we look at the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without damaging official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development aid.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditure of previous years or the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no rule and each chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, believe that each euro borrowed equals one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often emission reduction projects that are based on more effective technologies), it is mistaken to present a euro that will be recovered as the equivalent of one euro being donated... As a matter of course, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted for its commitments.
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see it for its own eyes.
It is the only EU country that so often uses the loan.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, comply with their commitments to 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions in time and, on the other hand, in relation to real financial effort.
Spending just €36.1 million, he manages to give the impression that he spends €420 million “new and additional,” as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems Bercy has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States going to continue to donate when they can simply lend?) as in negotiations, since the developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a detail, relatively short-term, in relation to the whole of climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012 with the intention of fulfilling its commitments and in the same way as the other European Union countries.
But in particular, France could push forward the debates on betting at stake in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of computing loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additional character” and the use of loans would help improve the level of international trust needed to advance negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old ingested 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value considering the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", purchased in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years old usually consumes in four meals and a snack a day.
These meals taken as a model, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The dish balance is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as potential or likely carcinogens, and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances susceptible to acting as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Center for Research on Cancer.
“Although, in virtually all cases, legal limits for each of the chemicals individually are not exceeded, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE pollutants is worrying,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about a twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide prohibited in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were dressed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk generated by these “pollutant cocktails” for the consumer “is likely underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the seriousness of the situation" to impose a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
